terms.interesting: Its name 'Mother of Thousands' reffers to its ability to propagate vegetatively from plantlets that develop on phylloclade margins.

It has a long history of cultivation as an ornamental plant, grown across the Mediterranean region, and later France (where it is used in perfumery), the Netherlands (a major centre of cultivation) and elsewhere.
The leaves move in response to light levels, opening in high ambient light (in the day) and closing at low light levels (at night).
The American sycamore is able to endure a big city environment and was formerly extensively planted as a shade tree.
The berry is attractive and familiar look make it dangerous for children, because it is toxic.
They are commonly planted in butterfly gardens as a nectar source. It is harvested for oil, which is used in perfumery; it is blended with sandalwood oil to produce 'attar genda' perfume.
